# /brain

The user's permanent second brain lives at `{{REPO}}`. Its own
`CLAUDE.md` is the authoritative protocol — read it before writing anything.

## Retrieving

1. Prefer the MCP tools if connected: `brain_search` (current knowledge only,
   retry with 2-3 lexical variants before concluding a miss), `brain_read`
   (full note with supersede history), `brain_links` (what references a note
   and what it references — use after a good hit to pull in its neighbours,
   which search may miss because they never repeat the term), `brain_recent`.
2. No MCP? Work directly: `cd {{REPO}}`, start from
   `knowledge/index.md`, search with `rg` (archive/, vault/, journal/ and
   inbox/ are already excluded — results are current canonical by
   construction) or `bin/brain search "..."`.
3. Only present `status: current` content as true today. Archived notes are
   history — cite them only as "previously…".

## What earns a note

Full policy: "What earns a note" in the repo's CLAUDE.md. In short — capture
the WHY, not the what. The what is recoverable from git, files and calendars;
the reasoning is gone within a week.

- Capture freely: a decision AND the alternatives rejected; a stated preference
  or constraint; a fact about the user's world that can't be inferred; an answer
  that cost real effort.
- Never: anything derivable from code or public docs, transient state,
  credentials, or a restatement of what was just done.
- Ask first, every time: a named person's private life, health, finances or
  relationships — this repo auto-pushes to GitHub.

Capture is cheap because inbox/ sits outside default search and consolidation
deletes the noise; canonical notes are expensive because they rank in every
future search. Capture generously, promote strictly.

Offer, don't nag: when something passes the bar mid-conversation, say so in one
line and carry on. Do not save the offer for the end of the session — by then
the reasoning is already gone.

## Saving

- Quick fact or thought: `brain_capture` tool, or
  `bin/brain capture "..." --commit` — lands in inbox/, committed and pushed.
- Structured note: `bin/brain new <kind> "<title>" --topics a,b`, fill body
  and aliases, then `bin/brain lint` and commit.
- A fact CHANGED: follow the supersede protocol in the repo's CLAUDE.md —
  never edit meaning in place, never delete.

## Health

`bin/brain doctor` — hooks, backup freshness, index, inbox backlog, lint.
